Problem Statement

Repeat the process shown so far in this module to build a decision tree on the mortality data we used earlier in this course. Use actual_cnt = 0 and actual_cnt > 0 as the target variable.

library(caret)  #ML 
library(rpart)  #Decision Trees
library(rpart.plot)  #Decision Tree plots
library(scales)  #formatting
library(kableExtra)  #formatting
library(tidyverse)  #tidy data
library(pROC)

# Set threshold
thresh_1 = 0.5
Prep Data

For the prescribed target variable I created a factor variable named ‘is_claimant’ for which:
- actual_cnt == 0 -> ‘0’
- actual_cnt > 0 -> ‘1’

For variables to include in the modeling, I removed any that were collinear with the target in a non-meaningful way; e.g. it’s not useful to know that actual_cnt will be split on, since we used it to define our target.

# Import csv mort_raw <- read.csv(
# 'D:/Dropbox/PACP/data/soa_mortality_data.csv' )
mort_raw <- read.csv("/users/werlindo/Dropbox/PACP/data/soa_mortality_data.csv")

# create binarized target
mort_raw$is_claimant[mort_raw$actual_cnt == 0] = 0
mort_raw$is_claimant[mort_raw$actual_cnt > 0] = 1
# table(mort_raw$is_claimant)
mort_raw$is_claimant <- as.factor(mort_raw$is_claimant)  # This is to force the logistic regression to predict 0/1

# select variables available for training Take off actual_cnt and
# actual_face because, then you are using the target to predict :)
mort <- mort_raw[, setdiff(colnames(mort_raw), c("test", "X", "policy.number", 
    "actual_cnt", "actual_face", "year"))]

# split data into training vs testing
set.seed(2425)
train_pct <- 0.8

train <- createDataPartition(mort_raw$is_claimant, p = train_pct, list = FALSE)

# allocate datasets
mort_train <- mort[train, ]
dim(mort_train)
## [1] 400000     17
mort_test <- mort[-train, ]
dim(mort_test)
## [1] 100000     17
# Set the formula with all variables
mort_dt_f <- as.formula(paste("is_claimant~", paste(names(mort_train[, -(which(names(mort_train) == 
    "is_claimant"))]), collapse = " + ")))
# Fit a decision tree, method = 'class' ensures the target is treated as a
# categorical variable
mort_dt <- rpart(mort_dt_f, data = mort_train, method = "class", control = rpart.control(minbucket = 5, 
    cp = 1e-05, maxdepth = 5), parms = list(split = "gini"))

# Plot the tree
rpart.plot(mort_dt)

# look at the print summary
print(mort_dt)

# look at the complexity parameter
printcp(mort_dt)

## 4 0.0000100      9   0.72635 0.73237 0.009938
plotcp(mort_dt)

# Extract the optimal complexity of the tree by taking the one with the
# minimum xerror
mort_dt$cptable[which.min(mort_dt$cptable[, "xerror"]), "CP"]
## [1] 1e-05
# prune the tree
mort_dt_pruned_1 <- prune(mort_dt, cp = mort_dt$cptable[which.min(mort_dt$cptable[, 
    "xerror"]), "CP"])

# Plot the tree
rpart.plot(mort_dt_pruned_1)

Went through one pruning based on minimum CV error, but the post-pruning tree is identical to the first one (We saw the same situation in the example in the lecture materials).

For fun lets look at some validation metrics.

Run predictions:
# Predictions
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# Predict the probabilities
mort_dt_res_probs <- predict(mort_dt_pruned_1, newdata = mort_train, type = "prob")

# Create dataframe of predictions
mort_dt_res_preds <- data.frame(thresh_1 = as.factor(1 * (mort_dt_res_probs[, 
    2] > thresh_1)))
Build confusion matrix:
# Confusion Matrices
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------

# Create confusion matrices for the predictions
mort_dt_cm_1 <- confusionMatrix(mort_dt_res_preds$thresh_1, mort_train$is_claimant)

# Create dataframe of confusion matrices
mort_res_cm_df <- data.frame(as.data.frame.matrix(mort_dt_cm_1$table))

# Some column naming to support final output
mort_res_cm_df <- rownames_to_column(mort_res_cm_df, var = "Prediction")
colnames(mort_res_cm_df)[2:3] <- c("0", "1")

kable(mort_res_cm_df, caption = "Confusion Matrix | Mortality Data | Training Dataset | Decision Tree | Threshold = 50%") %>% 
    kable_styling(full_width = FALSE) %>% column_spec(2, border_left = T) %>% 
    add_header_above(c(` ` = 1, Reference = 2))

ROC/AUC:
# ROC Curve
# -------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Get ROC curve
plot(roc(as.numeric(mort_train$is_claimant), as.numeric(mort_dt_res_probs[, 
    2])), col = "red", main = "ROC Curve  - Mortality Dataset - Training - Decision Tree")

# AUC
# -------------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Get AUC for each model, put into matrix
a1 <- auc(mort_train$is_claimant, as.numeric(mort_dt_res_preds$thresh_1))
# a2 <- auc(mort_train$target, as.numeric(mort_dt_res_preds$thresh_2)) a3 <-
# auc(mort_train$target, as.numeric(mort_dt_res_preds$thresh_3))
aaa <- rbind(a1)

# Create df for eventual display
mort_dt_aucs <- data.frame(Threshold = c(thresh_1), AUC = aaa)
rownames(mort_dt_aucs) <- c()

# Make a kable
kable(mort_dt_aucs, caption = "AUC - Mortality Dataset Predictions | Training Dataset | Decision Tree") %>% 
    kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)

Not the most impressive results. One thing that sticks out right away is that looking at the confusion matrix, the precision rate is not great:
False Positives (FP) = 4,242
True Positives (TP) = 3,074
Precision = TP/(FP+TP) = 0.420175.

But since this is an exercise in getting familiar with the methodology and code, let’s finish off by running the same diagnostics against test data.

Confusion Matrix for test data:

    2] > thresh_1)))
